english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Tidal Faithfulness
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The hamlet of Bald Mountain was cramped and shabby. In the cyclical year of Yongnak, I came here in exile, suffering through the torrential heat and rains. It was then I first built a hall at the foot of the mountain. Upon its completion, I climbed to survey it and considered what name to inscribe. The morning and evening winds, the drifting smoke, the changing seasons that surround this hall—all these are commonplace sights, worn thin from viewing, unworthy of being chosen as a name.

    Yet observing closely, I saw how the many waters of the valleys merged, embracing Lookout Mountain, flowing westward until they arrived before my hall in the shape of a drawn bow. Within a few miles they reached the river and entered the sea. The tides that pass before this hall never fail to keep their time. Here was a name worthy of my dwelling—a way to remind myself of a lesson. Since this water exists, so too does this tide. Has it ever, even once, broken its promise in a single day? As for myself, I lacked genuine learning in youth and was not sincere in heart, and so won no trust from friends. This is why I faced lawsuits and rejection. Yet I have never blamed Heaven or resented men for it. By calling the tide "faithfulness," I wish only to inscribe this virtue upon my heart.

    While dwelling in this hall, I must strive earnestly to follow the ancients: to conduct myself with reverence, to act with simplicity, and to deal with others in good faith. Only then will I do justice to the meaning of this name. When Liu Zongyuan was exiled to the Xiang River, he named a stream "Valley of Folly" as a rebuke to himself. I, by contrast, have given the tide a beautiful name—though our methods differ, both carry a cautionary meaning. The nature of tides has long been discussed. The old explanation held that the primordial breath rises and falls through the vast heavens, that the earth, riding the force of water, ascends and descends with this cosmic breath. When the breath rises and the earth sinks, the sea swells upward as a flood tide. When the breath falls and the earth floats, the waters recede as an ebb tide. Through each day and night, yin and yang rise and fall twice, so tides and ebbs occur twice daily. This ancient teaching was transmitted thus, and even Zhang Zai's *Correcting Youthful Ignorance* affirmed it, saying that the earth's rising and sinking can be verified through the tides themselves.

    Yet Lu Zhao of Tang offered another view: "The sun strikes the water, causing tides; the moon departs from the sun, making tides great." Here was a different insight altogether. But Master Zhu Xi, after careful consideration, doubted that either was entirely true. He taught instead that tides depend wholly upon the moon. When the moon is at the east-west cardinal points, tides swell in the east and west. When the moon is at the north-south cardinal points, tides level out north and south. In the daily cycle, the sun travels one degree while the moon travels thirteen degrees and more. Thus the moon's setting in the west always lags behind the sun's by three quarters of an hour, and the tides arrive in the same manner. From new moon to full moon, a night's tide constantly lags. From full moon to dark moon, a day's tide again lags. Before and after new and full moons, the moon moves slightly faster, so the three days before the dark moon see strong tides, and the three days after the new moon see powerful tides—likewise at the full moon. During the quarter moons, the moon moves more slowly, so tides arrive with somewhat less force. Within a month, tides peak after new and full moons. Within a year, tides peak in spring and autumn. In spring and summer, daytime tides run great; in autumn and winter, nighttime tides run great. A year's spring and autumn resemble a month's new and full moons—these are Heaven and Earth's constant measures.

    When I observe the external world, I see Heaven and Earth's opening and closing, the spirits' extending and contracting, heat and cold's coming and going, even unto plants' flourishing and withering, blooming and falling. Within myself, through all activity and stillness, speech and silence, down to the breath's rising and falling through nose and mouth—all arise from yin and yang combining and dispersing. By extending this principle, one can understand the tide's swelling and shrinking. The world speaks merely of morning tides and evening ebbs as a single breath cycling and returning, unaware that what is born from yin and grows through yang is of itself endless. If Heaven and Earth were but a great forge burning down creation to cinders, how could the already-dispersed breath linger on? And how could the cosmic forge employ such spent breath to fashion what is newly unfolding?

    Since I have named the hall by the tidal faithfulness, I venture to speak of this as well. I once studied Mencius's method of observing streams but grasped not its essence. Only when I read Master Cheng's words on observing streams—"Seeing how the water flows without ceasing, awakens one to the infinite vastness of what has root"—did I begin to glimpse the gateway. As for the Master's sigh by the stream, born from the stirring of Heaven's workings, perceiving the infinite expanse of the Way's substance—what Cheng Zi called "becoming one body with the Way" expresses this fully. Though I cannot yet achieve it, I wish earnestly to learn.
  footnotes:
    - Yongnak (永樂) refers to the reign period of King Taejong of Joseon (1401-1418); the cyclical year Gapsin (甲申) would be 1404.
    - Liu Zongyuan (773-819) was a Tang poet and official who named a stream "Valley of Folly" (愚溪) during his exile as a form of self-rebuke.
    - Master Zhu Xi's lunar theory of tides, presented here, represents medieval Neo-Confucian cosmology's sophisticated understanding of celestial mechanics.
    - The reference to observing streams alludes to Mencius 2A:2, where the Master speaks of observing water to understand human nature—a classic metaphor for self-cultivation.
    - Cheng Zi (程子) refers to Cheng Yi (1033-1107), a foundational Neo-Confucian philosopher whose teachings on the Way deeply influenced Korean literati.
